author: Ordoferrum
body: Heard so many stories like this. Nobody back then thought bitcoin would raise as high as it has though.   Well some people did, but most people just presumed they were deluded. Back when I was buying stuff on the markets I did not have much spare cash to invest. But I did tell my dad he should buy a few coins as he did do investing. He still mentions it nowadays about how he should have listened to me.¬†

author: Skittlebrau46
body: Yeah. Any market is going to have those ‚Äúif I just known‚Äù stories. I think BTC was such a cutting edge thing that no one seemed to really understand and appealed to the early adopters who were more likely to cash out for something fun and quick and go back to life before it all disappeared‚Ä¶ so there are lots of those ‚Äúif only‚Äù stories attached.   The folks who still have wallets with known coin they can‚Äôt access, hurt a lot more than my stupid story about spending it 15 years too early.

author: talkingwolf695
body: You gotta educate yourself instead of asking these very simple questions. No offense. Just take a look at the circulating supply and then compare with the market cap. It gets very complicated fast. But generally to keep it simple, market cap = dollars of investors in the token. Circulating supply = how many exist. If there's 1 million tokens, and 1 million dollars of investors money in the token, it'll be worth $1. Now shib has 500 trillion? It needs 500T of dollars to reach $1. It's currently at 16billion $ market cap. Even a penny is impossible with the current project being as is with burn mechanisms.
